The court has a discretion to admit relevant expert evidence despite failure to serve a report in compliance with this rule (or any order or direction): Cameron v Baker  (NSWCA, Reynolds, Samuels and Mahoney JJA, No 316/79, 6 August 1980, unreported, BC8000055); Dawson v Hall  (NSWCA, Clarke, Meagher, Handley JJA, 29 July 1994, unreported, BC9402852). Subject to the possible exercise of the discretion to extend time for service (see 
[31.28.15]
), the discretion conferred by the present rule is limited by the requirement that the court is satisfied there are “exceptional circumstances” warranting the grant of leave. The rule does not set out what constitutes “exceptional circumstances” — that assessment must depend on a careful consideration of the facts of the individual case: AWA v Independent News Auckland [1996] 2 NZLR 184  at 186. Beyond that generality, in order to constitute “exceptional circumstances warranting the granting of leave” the matters relied on:

The considerations as to whether to otherwise order are similar to those in permitting a party to rely upon a report not served within time (see 
[31.28.5]
). However, exceptional circumstances are not required to be demonstrated.

Although the rules make separate provision for joint expert conferences (UCPR r 31.24), and concurrent evidence (UCPR 
r 31.35
) the two concepts are related. The utility of the joint conference procedure depends on whether or not the respective experts address the same relevant and material facts, and are aware of the issues and opinions that are in contention: see Garling J “Concurrent Expert Evidence: Reflections and Development” (2011) 49 Law Society Journal 10. The same considerations apply to the effectiveness and efficiency of concurrent evidence: see Willett v United Concrete Pty Ltd (2009) 190 IR 28; [2009] NSWSC 957;  BC200908675  at [54]–[56].
